      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "\"Hungry goblins,\" you say? Well, in my world, every struggling starter feels like a horde of tiny, demanding goblins vying for the last bit of flour! To stick to the science, the imbalance usually stems from the *ratio* of the different microbes and the environment. If the acidic bacteria—the *Lactobacilli*—take over too quickly, they produce too much acid, which lowers the $\\text{pH}$ dramatically. This highly acidic environment is frankly hostile territory for many of the more vigorous yeast strains, effectively starving them out or slowing their metabolic rate until they're just shuffling around like sad, damp little goblins.\n\nAnother cause is the specific flour you're using, which dictates the available nutrients for different microbes. Different flours, like rye versus white, attract different initial microbial communities. You need a diverse, resilient community, not just one dominant group of acid-lovers. If you're feeding too little, or with too much water, the microbial population density drops, making it easy for a single, overly aggressive strain to dominate the fermentation process.\n\nThink of it this way: a perfect starter is like a well-organized, slightly chaotic village where the farmers (yeast",
